# Caching & CDN Specification

## Overview

Skaia deployments sit behind Cloudflare (or similar CDN). API responses must
NEVER be cached by intermediaries. Static assets and uploads have explicit
long-lived cache policies. This spec documents the caching rules and the
patterns that prevent stale data.

---

## Layer 1: Go Application (`WriteJSON` / `WriteError`)

All JSON API responses set:

```
Cache-Control: no-store, no-cache, must-revalidate
Pragma: no-cache
```

This is enforced in `backend/internal/utils/http.go`. Every handler that
returns JSON goes through `WriteJSON`, so no individual handler needs to set
cache headers.

## Layer 2: nginx Reverse Proxy

Generated by `cmd/grengo/nginx.go` via `grengo nginx reload`.

| Location         | Cache-Control                         | Purpose                  |
| ---------------- | ------------------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| `/api/`          | `no-store, no-cache, must-revalidate` | All API endpoints        |
| `/config/`       | `no-store, no-cache, must-revalidate` | Config/page endpoints    |
| `/uploads/*`     | `public, max-age=2592000` (30 days)   | User-uploaded files      |
| `/assets/*`      | `public` + immutable hash in filename | Vite-built static assets |
| `/ws`, `/api/ws` | N/A (WebSocket upgrade)               | Real-time connection     |

**IMPORTANT**: The nginx config at `nginx/default.conf` is AUTO-GENERATED.
Do not edit it directly. Edit the template in `cmd/grengo/nginx.go` and run
`grengo nginx reload` to regenerate.

`backend/frontend/nginx/default.conf` is the Docker image's internal nginx
config (for the frontend container variant). It is separate from the runtime
reverse-proxy config.

## Layer 3: CDN (Cloudflare)

Cloudflare respects `Cache-Control` headers. With `no-store`, API responses
are not cached at the edge. However:

**CDN caches by URL**, not by response content. This means:

- `GET /config/pages/index` is ONE cache key regardless of which page is the
  landing page. If cached before `no-store` headers were deployed, Cloudflare
  may serve stale content until the cache entry expires or is purged.

- `GET /config/pages/{slug}` has a UNIQUE cache key per page. Changing the
  landing page to a different slug hits a different URL.

### CDN-Proof Pattern: Two-Step Slug Resolution

The frontend resolves the landing page in two steps:

1. `GET /config/pages/landing-slug` → `{ "slug": "my-page" }` (tiny, never cached)
2. `GET /config/pages/my-page` → full page data (unique URL per page)

This avoids the single-cache-key problem entirely.

### CDN-Proof Pattern: WebSocket Push

For real-time updates, the backend pushes full data through WebSocket:

- `landing_page_changed` → full page object via `page:update`
- `page_updated` → full page object via `page:update`

WebSocket is not subject to CDN caching.

## Anti-Patterns

1. **Returning different resources from the same URL.** A single URL must
   always return the same type of resource. `/config/pages/index` violates
   this by returning whichever page is currently configured as landing.
   The frontend works around this with the two-step pattern above.

2. **HTTP redirects from API endpoints.** `fetch()` follows 307 redirects
   transparently, but the redirected response can confuse frontend logic
   that expects specific response shapes. Don't redirect API endpoints.

3. **Relying on CDN cache purge for correctness.** Cache purge is eventual
   and requires API keys / dashboard access. Design data flows to work
   without purging — use unique URLs or WebSocket push.

4. **Editing the generated `nginx/default.conf` directly.** It will be
   overwritten on next `grengo nginx reload`. Edit `cmd/grengo/nginx.go`.
